Dunne went to [[Amherst College]] and received his Ph.D. in the Study of Religion from [[Harvard University]] in 1999. According to his faculty profile, his work "focuses on [[Buddhist philosophy]] and contemplative practice, especially in dialog with [[Cognitive science|Cognitive Science]]. His publications range from technical works on Buddhist epistemology to broader works on the nature of Buddhist contemplative practices such as [[Mindfulness]]."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alc.wisc.edu/about/faculty/john-d-dunne|title=John D. Dunne {{!}} Department of Asian Languages and Cultures|website=alc.wisc.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref> He occasionally teaches for Buddhist communities, most notably the [[Upaya Institute and Zen Center]]. He was a student of [[Tulku Urgyen Rinpoche]] and now studies with Tulku Urgyen's sons [[Chökyi Nyima Rinpoche]] and [[Yongey Mingyur Rinpoche]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.upaya.org/2016/12/dunne-bodhidharma-himalayan-eyes-1-n/|title=Dharma talk "Bodhidharma Through Himalayan Eyes" (Part 1) - Upaya Zen Center|last=|first=|date=2016-12-19|newspaper=Upaya Zen Center|access-date=2017-02-11|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|work=|language=en-US|via=}}</ref>
Dunne is the author of ''Foundations of Dharmakīrti's Philosophy'', part of Wisdom Publications' "Studies in Indian and Tibetan Buddhism Series," a study of the thought of the important 7th century Buddhist philosopher [[Dharmakīrti]].<ref>''Foundations of Dharmakīrti's Philosophy'' by John D. Dunne. Wisdom Publications: 2004. {{ISBN|086171184X}}, 9780861711840</ref>
